WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.800
To the session on cancer detection, interception across tumor

2
00:00:03.840 --> 00:00:07.460
types, addressing modifiable risk factors for early

3
00:00:07.480 --> 00:00:11.300
detection. And here you see a QR code that

4
00:00:11.380 --> 00:00:15.100
you can scan for eventually asking questions

5
00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:16.800
through the remote system.

6
00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:26.520
I'm Adriana Albini from the National Cancer Institute of

7
00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:27.960
Italy, and

8
00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:32.860
I've been working for over 30 years on cancer

9
00:00:32.920 --> 00:00:33.980
prevention, and

10
00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:38.020
I had the privilege to be the founding

11
00:00:38.900 --> 00:00:42.800
chair of the Cancer Prevention Working Group

12
00:00:43.260 --> 00:00:46.980
that has started in 2021

13
00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:50.960
after I was in the ACR board and has now 7,000

14
00:00:51.020 --> 00:00:54.220
members, which I think is really very good for

15
00:00:55.280 --> 00:00:56.180
our field.

16
00:00:57.720 --> 00:01:00.840
And I'm going to give just a couple of minutes of introduction.

17
00:01:01.260 --> 00:01:02.920
Our session has to deal

18
00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:07.920
mostly with emerging strategies aiming, identifying, intervening

19
00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:12.000
cancer development at early stages across multiple types, with

20
00:01:12.020 --> 00:01:15.600
attention to modifiable risk factors and precancerous

21
00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:19.680
oncogenic drivers, going into the way of more

22
00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:20.860
proactive prevention

23
00:01:22.100 --> 00:01:24.600
models. And the session

24
00:01:27.060 --> 00:01:31.000
deals with, this is a slide that I

25
00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:33.860
took from Phil Castle, had a session yesterday,

26
00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:37.060
of the various stages of tumor progression.

27
00:01:37.420 --> 00:01:41.280
What we can do from normal cells, where we can do

28
00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:45.050
primary prevention, to the interception phase,

29
00:01:45.610 --> 00:01:48.700
and then what is therapy and mitigation.

30
00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:52.710
Of course, we want to work very early on, and this is

31
00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:56.360
many attempts, and I was very pleased to see how much

32
00:01:56.480 --> 00:02:00.300
attention is to early detection and interception at

33
00:02:00.380 --> 00:02:01.220
this meeting.

34
00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:03.880
So after this

35
00:02:05.100 --> 00:02:08.549
mini introduction, I would like to let the

36
00:02:09.700 --> 00:02:13.660
podium to the first lecturer, Margie Lee Clapper.

37
00:02:14.260 --> 00:02:17.940
She is a professor, Samuel Hemming-Thall Endowed Chair in

38
00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:21.950
Cancer Prevention, and Director of the Cancer Prevention Interception

39
00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:26.040
Targeted Agent Discovery Program at Fox Chase Cancer Center

40
00:02:26.100 --> 00:02:30.040
in Philadelphia. For more than 30 years, her basic research laboratory

41
00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:33.520
has been focused on development of agents for the prevention of cancer.

42
00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:37.220
Margie Clapper pioneered one of the first U.S.

43
00:02:37.340 --> 00:02:40.910
basic research programs focused on cancer prevention, early detection

44
00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:44.800
in high-risk populations. Her research focuses including

45
00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:48.780
genetic susceptibility, hormonal influence, and preventive

46
00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:52.160
agents, as well as early detection strategies.

47
00:02:53.100 --> 00:02:57.049
So Margie, the podium is yours, and I'm just going

48
00:02:57.080 --> 00:02:58.520
to start your presentation.

49
00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:05.280
So thank you so much, Dr. Albini, and

50
00:03:06.140 --> 00:03:09.500
thanks for the invitation. It's certainly a pleasure to be here and share our data

51
00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:11.120
with you. It's quite the honor.

52
00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:14.680
So I have nothing to disclose.

53
00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:19.260
I wanted to look back and share with you the progress we've made in cancer

54
00:03:19.280 --> 00:03:20.970
prevention over the last 100 years.

55
00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:25.600
And in the 1930s, we began to understand that chemical carcinogenesis was a

56
00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:29.400
two-stage process consisting of initiation as well as

57
00:03:29.420 --> 00:03:33.109
promotion. And about 30 years later, Lea Wattenberg and several

58
00:03:33.260 --> 00:03:36.960
other investigators realized that we could actually reverse this

59
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.820
process, and he coined the term chemoprophylaxis.

60
00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:45.160
We then moved into a very exciting era of chemoprevention and

61
00:03:45.560 --> 00:03:49.540
immunoprevention. I joined the field in the early '90s, and at that point,

62
00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:52.700
we were starting some very informative clinical trials,

63
00:03:53.100 --> 00:03:57.000
chemoprevention trials, which really paved the way for future

64
00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:58.040
direction in the field.

65
00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:03.530
And then in 2011, Dr. Elizabeth Blackburn introduced

66
00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:07.260
the term cancer interception, and she stressed that this was an

67
00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:11.370
active process as compared to passive smoking cessation,

68
00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:11.920
et cetera.

69
00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:16.820
She equated it interestingly to intercepting a pass during a

70
00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:20.200
football game, and in this case, keeping that

71
00:04:20.240 --> 00:04:24.080
precancerous lesion in a sort of quiescent

72
00:04:24.200 --> 00:04:27.940
state and not allowing it to move into an advanced

73
00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:31.580
tumor. So of course, the topic of our discussion today.

74
00:04:35.080 --> 00:04:38.940
Now with next-gen sequencing, we've come to understand that this is a very complex

75
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:42.240
area, in terms of the formation of this precancerous

76
00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:45.600
lesion. A number of changes are occurring,

77
00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:50.040
intricate changes, and these are not only in the epithelial cells, but

78
00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:53.060
also in the supportive stroma, as well as in the immune

79
00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:57.120
compartment. There are many investigators that are

80
00:04:57.160 --> 00:04:59.720
trying to delineate these events.

81
00:05:00.280 --> 00:05:02.820
As you can imagine, it's quite a difficult task,

82
00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:07.150
but in part, this is being done through the generation of the Precancer

83
00:05:07.340 --> 00:05:11.000
Atlas. So this is an initiative from the NCI that was part of the

84
00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:14.890
Moonshot initiative, and it's leading to the formation of a

85
00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:18.600
catalog of precancerous alterations for a number of

86
00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:19.720
solid tumors.

87
00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:24.560
And we're learning a lot from this multi-omics approach, looking at this at

88
00:05:24.650 --> 00:05:26.000
different molecular levels.

89
00:05:26.860 --> 00:05:30.440
So now we are sort of bombarded with a lot of

90
00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:34.220
data, a lot of big data, and the question is,

91
00:05:34.280 --> 00:05:38.160
which of these changes will be the most promising target for early

92
00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:38.890
interception?

93
00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:43.940
So I think these have to be the earliest identifiable alteration to get the

94
00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:44.920
biggest benefit.

95
00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:49.500
They should control a hub of downstream oncogenic

96
00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:50.020
signaling.

97
00:05:51.420 --> 00:05:55.300
Of course, they have to be exploitable, either with immune modulation or with

98
00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:59.160
small molecules. And to achieve specificity, we need to make

99
00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:02.860
sure that they are overexpressed in the tumor, as compared to the

100
00:06:02.900 --> 00:06:06.796
normal tissue.So the greatest

101
00:06:06.896 --> 00:06:10.856
need for these interceptive agents exists in those that are highest risk

102
00:06:10.896 --> 00:06:14.276
for cancer, including those that inherit a

103
00:06:14.316 --> 00:06:18.096
predisposition gene, and this has been our focus at Fox

104
00:06:18.176 --> 00:06:22.116
Chase. This is about 10% of all the tumors that form.

105
00:06:22.716 --> 00:06:26.706
And on the right-hand side, this table summarizes the most prevalent

106
00:06:26.896 --> 00:06:30.786
syndromes, and it's estimated there may be as many as 50 syndromes

107
00:06:30.836 --> 00:06:34.566
that are cancer-predisposing. I've listed the genes that are

108
00:06:34.636 --> 00:06:38.216
mutated, and you can see that they confer increased risk for a

109
00:06:38.255 --> 00:06:40.116
variety of different tumor types.

110
00:06:40.956 --> 00:06:44.256
Now, in general, the estimated lifetime risk for these

111
00:06:44.296 --> 00:06:48.246
individuals is 75% or more, and it can

112
00:06:48.336 --> 00:06:50.956
actually reach close to 100%.

113
00:06:52.376 --> 00:06:55.796
According to the Knudson two-hit hypothesis, those

114
00:06:55.916 --> 00:06:59.736
individuals who inherit a germline mutation in a tumor

115
00:06:59.816 --> 00:07:03.806
suppressor only need one additional hit to result in

116
00:07:03.896 --> 00:07:06.556
complete loss of tumor suppressor function.

117
00:07:07.276 --> 00:07:09.136
So we have a unique opportunity here.

118
00:07:09.516 --> 00:07:13.336
We have an opportunity to intervene in the heterozygous state very

119
00:07:13.516 --> 00:07:17.276
early in the carcinogenesis process, and I think importantly,

120
00:07:17.396 --> 00:07:21.376
in individuals who are otherwise healthy and asymptomatic.

121
00:07:22.076 --> 00:07:25.256
And we're hoping that the data that we gleaned from

122
00:07:26.156 --> 00:07:29.656
these populations will be readily applicable to sporadic

123
00:07:29.716 --> 00:07:32.196
cancer as well.

124
00:07:35.136 --> 00:07:38.916
So I think the greatest advancements in this area have been in the

125
00:07:38.976 --> 00:07:42.596
area of immunoprevention, and I'm sure you've already heard about this during this

126
00:07:42.656 --> 00:07:46.596
meeting. We're very enthusiastic about results that recently came

127
00:07:46.656 --> 00:07:46.796
out

128
00:07:47.856 --> 00:07:48.296
in this

129
00:07:49.856 --> 00:07:50.876
cancer paper,

130
00:07:52.196 --> 00:07:55.336
on the NUSTRO9 vaccine, which I will get to shortly.

131
00:07:56.036 --> 00:07:59.906
But this is focusing on the high-risk population

132
00:07:59.936 --> 00:08:03.886
with Lynch syndrome. These individuals inherit a mutation in

133
00:08:03.916 --> 00:08:06.716
the mismatch repair genes, one of the four genes.

134
00:08:06.996 --> 00:08:10.786
This is the most prevalent, being an incidence of about one in 300

135
00:08:11.116 --> 00:08:14.806
in terms of cancer syndromes, and it's conferring a risk for a variety of

136
00:08:14.836 --> 00:08:15.816
cancers as well.

137
00:08:17.456 --> 00:08:21.036
In these individuals, in cells that inherit a

138
00:08:21.496 --> 00:08:25.276
mismatch repair deficiency, there is slippage of the DNA

139
00:08:25.496 --> 00:08:29.376
polymerase. We get the generation of insertions

140
00:08:29.396 --> 00:08:30.136
and deletions,

141
00:08:31.176 --> 00:08:34.196
and the accumulation of mutations over time.

142
00:08:34.256 --> 00:08:38.156
And if it occurs in the coding region, we get the

143
00:08:38.196 --> 00:08:42.076
generation of frameshift peptides, which then promote tumorigenesis.

144
00:08:43.557 --> 00:08:47.496
These frameshift peptides are not only specific to these

145
00:08:47.536 --> 00:08:50.656
mutated cells, but they are also highly immunogenic.

146
00:08:51.676 --> 00:08:54.976
And the hypothesis was that they could be used for vaccine development.

147
00:08:55.956 --> 00:08:59.916
So this concept was tested initially by Matthias Klooer, who is now at the

148
00:08:59.936 --> 00:09:00.996
University of Heidelberg,

149
00:09:01.816 --> 00:09:05.516
in a Phase 1/2a trial. And in this case, he used three

150
00:09:05.556 --> 00:09:07.436
frameshift peptides. He

151
00:09:08.836 --> 00:09:12.196
vaccinated the Lynch carriers who had advanced stage colorectal

152
00:09:12.316 --> 00:09:15.356
cancer and found that this vaccine was

153
00:09:15.476 --> 00:09:19.456
well-tolerated, and more importantly, induced a robust immune

154
00:09:19.516 --> 00:09:20.156
response.

155
00:09:23.136 --> 00:09:26.896
So fast-forward, there are many initiatives in this area to try and develop

156
00:09:26.906 --> 00:09:29.396
vaccines for these particular populations.

157
00:09:29.416 --> 00:09:33.376
But as I mentioned, we are extremely excited about this most recent paper

158
00:09:33.396 --> 00:09:36.976
in "Nature Medicine," came out this year, showing the

159
00:09:37.016 --> 00:09:40.246
results from the first cohort who received this

160
00:09:40.296 --> 00:09:43.605
NU209 neoantigen vaccine. These are

161
00:09:43.796 --> 00:09:47.636
209 frameshift peptides that were specific for

162
00:09:47.856 --> 00:09:51.696
tumors from individuals with Lynch syndrome, and they were

163
00:09:51.776 --> 00:09:55.746
used to develop the vaccine. In this case, these

164
00:09:55.776 --> 00:09:59.096
individuals had not had a cancer in the last six months.

165
00:09:59.996 --> 00:10:03.376
They were vaccinated initially and then got a booster eight weeks later.

166
00:10:03.836 --> 00:10:07.816
They were followed over a one-year period with colonoscopies at baseline,

167
00:10:08.216 --> 00:10:11.696
as well as at the end of this one-year

168
00:10:12.256 --> 00:10:12.676
period.

169
00:10:14.856 --> 00:10:16.876
The data look extremely promising.

170
00:10:17.276 --> 00:10:20.646
In the left-hand panel, they have used ELISpot

171
00:10:20.716 --> 00:10:24.705
analyses looking at interferon gamma and see a very

172
00:10:24.776 --> 00:10:27.256
robust immune response in those individuals

173
00:10:28.936 --> 00:10:32.396
post-vaccine as compared to baseline.

174
00:10:33.076 --> 00:10:36.296
And importantly, they find that this response is durable.

175
00:10:36.736 --> 00:10:40.236
So 85% of those individuals had a positive immune

176
00:10:40.296 --> 00:10:43.036
response after the one-year duration.

177
00:10:43.756 --> 00:10:46.656
In a separate study, they looked to see how prevalent these

178
00:10:47.436 --> 00:10:51.136
frameshift peptides were across pre-cancers and cancers and

179
00:10:51.196 --> 00:10:54.606
found that of 115 frameshifts that they looked at,

180
00:10:55.436 --> 00:10:58.946
82% of the samples included these

181
00:10:58.976 --> 00:11:02.256
frameshift peptides, which suggests broad

182
00:11:02.296 --> 00:11:06.206
applicability and very exciting application in

183
00:11:06.236 --> 00:11:06.716
the future.

184
00:11:08.796 --> 00:11:12.516
So I mentioned we are now dealing with a lot of data that's coming

185
00:11:12.596 --> 00:11:16.476
out of omics platforms, and now the challenge is to figure out

186
00:11:16.616 --> 00:11:20.576
which of these targets are most promising. And it was the vision of Dr.

187
00:11:20.776 --> 00:11:23.316
Shizuko Sei at the Division of Cancer Prevention,

188
00:11:24.256 --> 00:11:28.156
NCI, to capture this and use it to

189
00:11:28.176 --> 00:11:31.776
fuel the drug development pipeline by creating the Cancer Prevention

190
00:11:31.876 --> 00:11:34.636
Interception Targeted Agent Discovery program.

191
00:11:35.276 --> 00:11:39.136
This was enthusiastically endorsed by NCI as well as many of

192
00:11:39.176 --> 00:11:42.956
us in the field. And the goal is to develop molecularly and

193
00:11:42.996 --> 00:11:46.936
immunologically targeted agents for the early interception of cancer

194
00:11:46.976 --> 00:11:50.246
in high-risk populations, including those with heritable syndromes.

195
00:11:50.906 --> 00:11:54.766
This started about four years ago with three founding centers, which included

196
00:11:54.776 --> 00:11:58.636
Fox Chase Cancer Center, Weill Cornell Medicine, as well as Baylor

197
00:11:58.676 --> 00:12:02.336
College of Medicine. And over the last four years, it's grown into

198
00:12:02.376 --> 00:12:05.886
14 participating centers, including a data coordinating

199
00:12:05.976 --> 00:12:09.444
center.And we are very excited to be part of this initiative.

200
00:12:10.004 --> 00:12:13.824
So what I'd like to do today is to share with you some of the interesting studies

201
00:12:13.864 --> 00:12:17.684
that are going on and some of the preliminary data that is being

202
00:12:17.724 --> 00:12:18.284
generated.

203
00:12:20.124 --> 00:12:24.064
So the first is a study that comes from investigators at Weill Cornell

204
00:12:24.164 --> 00:12:28.124
Medicine. This is Dr. Vivek Mittal's laboratory, and the studies

205
00:12:28.144 --> 00:12:31.304
were done in collaboration with his postdoc, Yongfeng Li.

206
00:12:32.824 --> 00:12:36.484
In this case, they are trying to intercept premalignant lung nodules,

207
00:12:37.444 --> 00:12:37.984
those

208
00:12:39.384 --> 00:12:43.204
lesions that show up on CT scans. These are very

209
00:12:43.244 --> 00:12:47.104
early lesions. They're called ground-glass opacities because they

210
00:12:47.144 --> 00:12:51.124
present as a hazy area on the scan, which can then

211
00:12:51.204 --> 00:12:52.264
increase in density,

212
00:12:53.144 --> 00:12:56.524
and become, over time, a full-blown

213
00:12:56.544 --> 00:12:57.564
adenocarcinoma.

214
00:12:58.424 --> 00:13:02.224
Now, these lesions are due normally to inflammation or viral

215
00:13:02.264 --> 00:13:06.094
infection, and these hazy areas are indicative

216
00:13:06.104 --> 00:13:09.564
of the thickening of the interstitial wall or

217
00:13:09.584 --> 00:13:11.164
collapse of the alveoli.

218
00:13:12.144 --> 00:13:15.804
And about 30% of these lesions that are seen as non-solid

219
00:13:16.244 --> 00:13:20.064
will go on to develop into invasive adenocarcinomas

220
00:13:20.444 --> 00:13:21.684
over a four-year period.

221
00:13:23.044 --> 00:13:24.303
So the

222
00:13:25.404 --> 00:13:28.404
Mittal laboratory has done whole exome sequencing.

223
00:13:28.784 --> 00:13:31.884
They've looked at over 200 of these lesions, and they

224
00:13:32.684 --> 00:13:35.964
found that even in the non-solid case, about

225
00:13:36.164 --> 00:13:39.244
25% of them are carrying mutant EGFR.

226
00:13:39.904 --> 00:13:43.384
This was quite surprising. And about 40% of the

227
00:13:43.424 --> 00:13:46.064
non-solid had mutations in KRAS.

228
00:13:46.994 --> 00:13:50.914
They looked at the subtype mutations and found the most prevalent for EGFR was

229
00:13:50.944 --> 00:13:54.604
the L858R, and for KRAS, the G12C.

230
00:13:55.324 --> 00:13:59.244
And their goal has been to try and develop vaccines against each of these

231
00:13:59.284 --> 00:14:00.364
mutated proteins.

232
00:14:01.944 --> 00:14:05.344
What I'll share with you today is the efforts for an EGFR

233
00:14:05.404 --> 00:14:05.944
vaccine.

234
00:14:06.784 --> 00:14:10.144
They're using the lipo nanoparticle platform, the mRNA

235
00:14:10.864 --> 00:14:14.494
platform, and the Moderna formulation, and they've modified this

236
00:14:14.544 --> 00:14:17.584
slightly by incorporating pseudouridine to increase

237
00:14:18.504 --> 00:14:22.444
stability. As you can see on the right-hand side, this vaccine is of

238
00:14:22.484 --> 00:14:25.444
very high quality, and they've achieved an encapsulation

239
00:14:25.844 --> 00:14:28.284
efficiency of over 90%.

240
00:14:30.384 --> 00:14:34.164
Fast-forward after a lot of analyses, they've gone on to look at in vivo

241
00:14:34.304 --> 00:14:37.824
efficacy, and, in this case, they have taken

242
00:14:37.884 --> 00:14:41.424
cells that are mutated for the L858R

243
00:14:42.324 --> 00:14:46.284
EGFR protein, and they've injected those cells into the tail vein of

244
00:14:46.324 --> 00:14:49.824
mice. They've then randomized their mice to receive either the

245
00:14:49.884 --> 00:14:53.144
vaccine or an empty lipo nanoparticle

246
00:14:54.064 --> 00:14:57.864
vaccine. And after a prime on day five, they have

247
00:14:57.904 --> 00:15:01.324
then done boosters at one-week

248
00:15:01.384 --> 00:15:04.704
intervals. And the data generated from this is extremely

249
00:15:04.744 --> 00:15:08.204
promising. They are seeing a robust antigen-specific

250
00:15:08.364 --> 00:15:12.004
response increase in CD8 T cells, and I think more

251
00:15:12.024 --> 00:15:15.124
importantly, they're seeing a dramatic reduction in tumor

252
00:15:15.204 --> 00:15:18.544
formation in the vaccine group as compared to the control.

253
00:15:19.304 --> 00:15:22.964
So more work to be done, but we are very excited about these preliminary data.

254
00:15:23.324 --> 00:15:26.984
They show great promise and feasibility of being able to target

255
00:15:27.584 --> 00:15:31.564
mutant EGFR. So the next steps are to look at the mechanisms that are

256
00:15:31.624 --> 00:15:35.384
underlying this anti-tumor efficacy and then to further

257
00:15:35.444 --> 00:15:36.844
optimize the vaccine.

258
00:15:37.784 --> 00:15:41.764
This was quite an aggressive model, so what they need to do now, and are pursuing,

259
00:15:41.884 --> 00:15:45.644
is to look in models that are less

260
00:15:45.764 --> 00:15:49.444
aggressive, as well as making sure that these models are

261
00:15:49.504 --> 00:15:50.624
relevant to humans.

262
00:15:53.664 --> 00:15:57.324
So the next example comes from my laboratory, where we're trying to target

263
00:15:57.384 --> 00:16:00.944
mutant p53 in the context of Li-Fraumeni syndrome.

264
00:16:01.764 --> 00:16:05.444
Again, a heritable syndrome where these individuals inherit a mutation

265
00:16:06.264 --> 00:16:08.384
in the tumor suppressor p53.

266
00:16:09.384 --> 00:16:12.844
This is a bit more rare than what you see for Lynch

267
00:16:12.924 --> 00:16:16.604
syndrome, but we think this is probably an underestimation of one in 5,000

268
00:16:16.644 --> 00:16:19.334
individuals. Again, a spectrum of tumors that

269
00:16:19.444 --> 00:16:23.004
these individuals are

270
00:16:23.024 --> 00:16:26.604
predisposed to, and in females, the incidence of

271
00:16:26.703 --> 00:16:28.323
cancer can be over 90%.

272
00:16:29.184 --> 00:16:33.084
And 50% of these tumors arise before age 40, so there's

273
00:16:33.164 --> 00:16:37.084
a great need, as you can see, to develop an interceptive therapy

274
00:16:37.124 --> 00:16:38.594
for this particular population.

275
00:16:39.664 --> 00:16:43.594
Now, interestingly, the germline mutations in p53 are very similar

276
00:16:43.624 --> 00:16:46.964
to what you would find that are acquired in solid tumors.

277
00:16:47.324 --> 00:16:50.984
The majority of them are in the DNA binding domain, which is from codon

278
00:16:51.224 --> 00:16:55.204
100 to 300, and there's two different types of

279
00:16:55.264 --> 00:16:57.684
mutations, those that disrupt the DNA binding

280
00:16:58.584 --> 00:17:02.454
domain and the binding of p53 to the DNA, and

281
00:17:02.504 --> 00:17:06.104
these are shown in blue. These are called contact mutations, and then there are

282
00:17:06.124 --> 00:17:10.045
structural mutations, which are the majority shown here in red,

283
00:17:10.585 --> 00:17:14.444
and they lead to unfolding of the protein or a decrease

284
00:17:14.484 --> 00:17:15.545
in thermal stability.

285
00:17:16.904 --> 00:17:17.744
Now, as you probably know,

286
00:17:18.944 --> 00:17:22.764
mutant p53 has been a target for drug

287
00:17:22.844 --> 00:17:26.004
development for decades, and there's probably 80

288
00:17:26.444 --> 00:17:30.104
compounds that have been synthesized to date that have been

289
00:17:31.404 --> 00:17:34.374
exploited to try and target this protein.

290
00:17:35.024 --> 00:17:38.684
So why is it so challenging? It's very difficult, as you can imagine, to

291
00:17:38.724 --> 00:17:42.164
reactivate a tumor suppressor as compared to inhibit an

292
00:17:42.224 --> 00:17:45.984
oncogenic protein. In this case, mutation of p53

293
00:17:46.124 --> 00:17:49.584
can lead to loss of function or gain of function.

294
00:17:50.644 --> 00:17:54.124
In addition, the mutant protein is highly unstable,

295
00:17:54.644 --> 00:17:58.574
so when we try to synthesize it and use it for in vitro analyses, it becomes

296
00:17:58.604 --> 00:18:02.314
very challenging, and it's estimated there's over 2,000

297
00:18:02.584 --> 00:18:05.704
different types of p53 mutations.

298
00:18:06.344 --> 00:18:09.624
So what have we learned to date? We've learned that some of these compounds that

299
00:18:09.644 --> 00:18:13.480
have been synthesized have off-target effects.There's been

300
00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:17.460
some success recently with an agent called rosatapopt, and this was

301
00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:20.330
developed by PMV Pharmaceuticals to target the

302
00:18:20.460 --> 00:18:24.440
Y220C mutation, which is about 1.8% of

303
00:18:24.540 --> 00:18:28.480
all p53 mutations. So it stresses that specificity

304
00:18:28.540 --> 00:18:32.120
may be important because they are seeing a response during

305
00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:36.050
preliminary clinical trials. However, they're seeing resistance, so that's

306
00:18:36.080 --> 00:18:38.880
something that we need to keep in mind going forward.

307
00:18:40.440 --> 00:18:40.700
So,

308
00:18:41.560 --> 00:18:44.520
as I mentioned, we're trying to develop this reactivator in the context of

309
00:18:44.540 --> 00:18:48.260
Li-Fraumeni syndrome. We're interested in developing an agent that can be

310
00:18:48.320 --> 00:18:52.220
administered orally and ideally reverse more than one type of

311
00:18:52.600 --> 00:18:55.960
p53 mutation, in particular, the hotspot mutations.

312
00:18:56.660 --> 00:19:00.580
This is a study that started in the laboratory

313
00:19:00.620 --> 00:19:03.980
of John Carren Nicholas at Fox Chase, where he did computational

314
00:19:04.040 --> 00:19:07.320
analyses, and he identified a cryptic pocket in

315
00:19:07.360 --> 00:19:10.790
p53. He then went on to screen over nine million

316
00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:14.760
compounds for their ability to interact with this pocket and ended up

317
00:19:14.800 --> 00:19:17.220
with some candidate in silico hits.

318
00:19:17.999 --> 00:19:19.490
Unfortunately, at this point, Dr.

319
00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:21.450
Carren Nicholas decided to go to industry,

320
00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:25.740
and I inherited the project about 18 months ago.

321
00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:28.700
So I want to tell you the progress we've made over that time.

322
00:19:29.260 --> 00:19:32.520
We immediately set up an operational procedure in the laboratory,

323
00:19:33.460 --> 00:19:36.060
and with the help of a very talented medicinal chemist, Dr.

324
00:19:36.320 --> 00:19:40.240
Broderick, we were able to design compounds and

325
00:19:40.320 --> 00:19:42.720
then send them to a CRO for synthesis.

326
00:19:43.080 --> 00:19:46.990
They then came back to my laboratory for functional analyses, as well as

327
00:19:47.020 --> 00:19:50.060
profiling for pharmacokinetic and metabolic

328
00:19:50.100 --> 00:19:54.000
properties. This was then used to reinform our

329
00:19:54.010 --> 00:19:57.960
design to enhance structure activity relationships, and we've done

330
00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:01.400
this for about 400 compounds, again in the last 18

331
00:20:01.700 --> 00:20:02.060
months.

332
00:20:03.140 --> 00:20:06.700
This led to some candidate leads that we then took into in vivo

333
00:20:06.820 --> 00:20:10.720
efficacy testing, and ultimately, we hope they will enter lead

334
00:20:10.860 --> 00:20:11.680
optimization.

335
00:20:14.500 --> 00:20:14.760
So,

336
00:20:15.600 --> 00:20:19.340
in the interest of time, I'll go right to the punchline, and that

337
00:20:19.500 --> 00:20:23.000
is that we have identified an agent which we call REM-491.

338
00:20:23.879 --> 00:20:27.540
We've used two types of in vitro assays to screen

339
00:20:27.920 --> 00:20:31.300
this particular agent for its ability to reactivate p53.

340
00:20:32.440 --> 00:20:36.020
And the one is the classic RTQ-PCR analysis of downstream

341
00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:39.920
targets of p53 signaling. We've looked at many, but we

342
00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:43.640
find that Nox and Puma are our best reporters of

343
00:20:43.650 --> 00:20:47.370
activity. And as you can see here, we see induction of

344
00:20:47.400 --> 00:20:51.320
both of these downstream targets in the

345
00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:55.220
p53 mutated cells. So Cal-33 are tongue

346
00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:59.280
carcinoma cells that carry the R175H mutation.

347
00:20:59.680 --> 00:21:03.540
And you can see we get nice induction of Nox and Puma in that cell line,

348
00:21:03.600 --> 00:21:07.500
but not in those that are wild type p53 or lacking p53, thus

349
00:21:07.540 --> 00:21:08.640
showing specificity.

350
00:21:10.300 --> 00:21:13.440
Our second assay is mitochondrial outer membrane

351
00:21:13.500 --> 00:21:17.320
permeabilization, which serves as a culmination of

352
00:21:17.340 --> 00:21:18.780
pro-apoptotic activity.

353
00:21:20.020 --> 00:21:22.020
And in the first set of

354
00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:26.420
bars here, this is again the Cal-33 cell line with the

355
00:21:26.500 --> 00:21:30.260
R175H in a homozygous state. We see dramatic

356
00:21:30.300 --> 00:21:32.970
induction of the MOMP activity,

357
00:21:33.780 --> 00:21:36.130
with an EC50 of about 40 nanomolar.

358
00:21:36.860 --> 00:21:40.380
Now, if we're interested in using this compound in Li-Fraumeni syndrome, in the

359
00:21:40.400 --> 00:21:43.080
end, we need to think about the heterozygous state.

360
00:21:43.120 --> 00:21:47.040
So in this case, we looked at R273 in heterozygous

361
00:21:47.720 --> 00:21:51.700
copy, and we find that the EC50 here is even much

362
00:21:51.780 --> 00:21:54.980
lower than 40 nanomolar, seeing a very robust

363
00:21:55.020 --> 00:21:58.860
response in these cells. And in both cases,

364
00:21:58.920 --> 00:22:02.580
the EC50 here is very compatible with ultimate

365
00:22:02.590 --> 00:22:04.860
translation into a clinical setting.

366
00:22:05.130 --> 00:22:06.860
So we were very delighted.

367
00:22:08.440 --> 00:22:11.910
What's even more important is that as we begin to look at other cell lines and

368
00:22:11.980 --> 00:22:15.910
other types of p53 mutations, we find that this compound is

369
00:22:15.980 --> 00:22:19.920
able to reactivate p53 across the board, suggesting that it

370
00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:23.380
might be very broad-based in its specificity.

371
00:22:23.560 --> 00:22:27.060
In each case, an EC50 that's about 50 or 40

372
00:22:27.460 --> 00:22:31.380
nanomolar, and my crude estimation based on reports

373
00:22:31.419 --> 00:22:35.290
in the literature is that we're able to reactivate about 25%

374
00:22:35.320 --> 00:22:38.120
to 30% of p53 mutations.

375
00:22:40.080 --> 00:22:42.080
In terms of the pharmacokinetic profile,

376
00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:46.280
if you give a single dose to a mouse and look at plasma

377
00:22:46.360 --> 00:22:49.980
levels after that, you see that the plasma levels are elevated

378
00:22:50.100 --> 00:22:53.950
above the estimated EC50 for in vivo for about

379
00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:58.080
20 hours. So this suggests that once-daily dosing will be

380
00:22:58.140 --> 00:23:02.040
appropriate. We've also tried to establish the maximum tolerated dose.

381
00:23:02.080 --> 00:23:05.760
We've not achieved it yet. We know it's over 400 milligrams per kilogram body

382
00:23:05.840 --> 00:23:09.260
weight, and we've seen no toxicity or any type of

383
00:23:09.380 --> 00:23:12.570
adverse effects with respect to blood biochemistry.

384
00:23:14.240 --> 00:23:18.000
So my last slide is to show you that we're able to actually get anti-tumor

385
00:23:18.060 --> 00:23:21.860
activity using REM-491 in vivo. So in this

386
00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:25.400
case, we took breast carcinoma cells bearing the R175H.

387
00:23:25.820 --> 00:23:29.220
We injected into mice, and then

388
00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:33.060
randomized them to receive either their vehicle, which was PEG 400,

389
00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:37.400
or REM-491. And the drug was administered

390
00:23:37.460 --> 00:23:41.390
over a 17-day period, and at the end, we looked for toxicity as

391
00:23:41.420 --> 00:23:43.670
well as an impact on tumor growth.

392
00:23:44.780 --> 00:23:48.440
Again, in this study, as before, we saw no evidence of

393
00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:52.600
adverse effects. As you can see, the body weight in the control group was very

394
00:23:52.620 --> 00:23:55.400
similar to that observed in the treated.

395
00:23:56.100 --> 00:24:00.020
We monitored tumor growth by caliper measurements through the old-fashioned way.

396
00:24:00.440 --> 00:24:04.180
We also did luciferase imaging and weighed the tumors

397
00:24:04.280 --> 00:24:07.760
at the end of the study. And in all

398
00:24:07.880 --> 00:24:11.850
instances, we saw a significant reduction in the size of

399
00:24:11.900 --> 00:24:14.520
those tumors in the treated group as compared to the

400
00:24:14.540 --> 00:24:18.524
control.So this was only the second in vivo experiment we've done.

401
00:24:18.644 --> 00:24:22.154
We have much more work to do, but we think this is very

402
00:24:22.264 --> 00:24:22.844
promising.

403
00:24:23.704 --> 00:24:27.644
So our current efforts are to improve the potency of this agent, and

404
00:24:27.664 --> 00:24:30.964
we're spending a lot of time trying to determine that indeed

405
00:24:31.184 --> 00:24:34.164
REM-491 is binding to mutated

406
00:24:34.184 --> 00:24:37.924
p53. This is extremely important to show target engagement.

407
00:24:39.164 --> 00:24:42.504
We're doing this in the next couple of weeks with X-ray

408
00:24:42.584 --> 00:24:46.484
crystallization, and we're also using computational approaches

409
00:24:46.864 --> 00:24:49.144
using Boltz2 and AlphaFold 3,

410
00:24:50.124 --> 00:24:52.724
to further confirm target engagement.

411
00:24:54.084 --> 00:24:57.864
So I hope I've convinced you that there's a lot of promise now,

412
00:24:58.264 --> 00:24:59.044
with a lot of

413
00:25:00.284 --> 00:25:03.924
new targets coming out of these omics platforms that can be used

414
00:25:04.044 --> 00:25:04.284
as

415
00:25:05.664 --> 00:25:08.844
strategies for intercepting pre-cancer to cancer transition.

416
00:25:09.404 --> 00:25:13.244
There's a critical unmet need, I can't stress this enough, for individuals who have

417
00:25:13.284 --> 00:25:17.064
hereditary cancer syndromes, and we think that valuable insight will be gained

418
00:25:17.124 --> 00:25:20.844
from these individuals that can then inform other strategies for early

419
00:25:20.864 --> 00:25:21.544
interception.

420
00:25:22.884 --> 00:25:23.144
There is

421
00:25:24.024 --> 00:25:27.304
great promise in using vaccines in the area of

422
00:25:27.384 --> 00:25:31.244
immuno-prevention, focusing on tumor-associated

423
00:25:31.324 --> 00:25:35.304
antigens as neoantigens. This is already in clinical trial, and I

424
00:25:35.424 --> 00:25:39.184
think this is going to be revolutionizing the field as we go forward.

425
00:25:40.004 --> 00:25:43.424
There's a lot of value in the in silico modeling, and I think one of our

426
00:25:43.444 --> 00:25:47.034
successes relies on using these new computational

427
00:25:47.104 --> 00:25:50.564
platforms to look at structure activity relationships and how we

428
00:25:50.624 --> 00:25:54.284
can then go on and tweak these agents and make them more potent.

429
00:25:54.294 --> 00:25:57.344
And finally, I hope I've convinced you that the field of cancer

430
00:25:58.044 --> 00:26:01.444
interception is better poised now than ever to impact this

431
00:26:01.504 --> 00:26:02.644
devastating disease.

432
00:26:04.104 --> 00:26:07.644
So with that, I'd like to thank those individuals who contributed to this

433
00:26:07.704 --> 00:26:10.984
research, not only those in my lab, but those in the CAPiT

434
00:26:11.064 --> 00:26:14.704
Network. We're very thankful for the

435
00:26:14.764 --> 00:26:18.544
NCI, for the funding, in particular, for the CAPiT project, and to Fox

436
00:26:18.584 --> 00:26:20.694
Chase, who has also supported this initiative.

437
00:26:21.214 --> 00:26:25.124
We're interested in expanding our cancer interception team, so if anybody

438
00:26:25.864 --> 00:26:29.224
would like to join us, I'd be delighted to hear from you. Thank you.

439
00:26:36.904 --> 00:26:40.884
Thank you very much, Dr Clapper, for your presentation.

440
00:26:41.464 --> 00:26:41.724
And

441
00:26:43.424 --> 00:26:45.204
for interest of time,

442
00:26:46.184 --> 00:26:49.364
we thought to do the discussion at the end

443
00:26:50.024 --> 00:26:53.524
all together so we can all sit here and discuss and answer

444
00:26:53.704 --> 00:26:54.464
questions.

445
00:26:55.364 --> 00:26:59.184
So I'm very glad to introduce our next speaker,

446
00:27:00.044 --> 00:27:03.604
which is also Dr Suzette Delaloge, a medical

447
00:27:03.644 --> 00:27:06.464
oncologist and researcher at Gustave Roussy

448
00:27:07.644 --> 00:27:11.624
in Paris, France, specializing in breast cancer and precision

449
00:27:11.704 --> 00:27:15.664
cancer prevention. She's the director of the Interception Personalized

450
00:27:15.764 --> 00:27:18.364
Cancer Prevention Program at Gustave Roussy.

451
00:27:18.864 --> 00:27:22.084
She coordinates major European initiatives and had

452
00:27:22.584 --> 00:27:25.724
roles in ESMO, ASCO, and international research networks.

453
00:27:26.404 --> 00:27:28.464
She has prestigious French and

454
00:27:29.644 --> 00:27:33.424
international honors for contribution to oncology research.

455
00:27:33.844 --> 00:27:34.784
So together with

456
00:27:35.804 --> 00:27:39.474
Professor Clapper, I'm very honored to have you as speaker in this

457
00:27:39.524 --> 00:27:40.464
session, please.

458
00:27:43.664 --> 00:27:47.344
Thank you. Thank you very much for the very nice introduction.

459
00:27:47.424 --> 00:27:51.124
So we will move a bit, and

460
00:27:51.144 --> 00:27:53.414
discuss more how to operate this

461
00:27:54.644 --> 00:27:58.564
precision prevention that we really wish to hear a lot about.

462
00:27:58.684 --> 00:27:59.744
Can you hear me properly?

463
00:28:00.984 --> 00:28:02.404
These are my disclosures.

464
00:28:04.024 --> 00:28:07.484
Okay, so what are the challenges and what is the

465
00:28:07.884 --> 00:28:11.864
vision? So very rapidly, because you've heard a lot about this precision

466
00:28:11.944 --> 00:28:15.584
prevention or personalized prevention, precision being a part of it

467
00:28:15.804 --> 00:28:19.584
during this meeting. The model, if we want to

468
00:28:19.624 --> 00:28:23.344
operate it, is that assessing the

469
00:28:23.444 --> 00:28:27.344
individual risk at a given time allows for the implementation

470
00:28:27.384 --> 00:28:31.264
of appropriate interventions for people who are identified at higher risk

471
00:28:31.304 --> 00:28:34.824
of cancer. And it's also of interest to identify people who would be

472
00:28:34.864 --> 00:28:37.844
at low risk of cancer. We will mostly

473
00:28:38.664 --> 00:28:40.724
discuss today higher risk, of course.

474
00:28:41.184 --> 00:28:44.564
So in identification of a situation with increased risk

475
00:28:44.904 --> 00:28:48.524
several years before the event will lead to propose very

476
00:28:48.564 --> 00:28:52.444
targeted, better interventions with what we have today and

477
00:28:52.504 --> 00:28:56.384
with what we will have soon, hopefully, in terms of early detection,

478
00:28:56.544 --> 00:28:59.264
screening, and also risk reduction and prevention.

479
00:28:59.584 --> 00:29:03.304
The idea would be to decrease the incidence of cancer, but also the

480
00:29:03.324 --> 00:29:07.284
incidence of bad cancer. So personalized interception is

481
00:29:07.364 --> 00:29:11.204
really a mix of risk assessment, early detection, and risk reduction

482
00:29:11.324 --> 00:29:13.984
all together, and avoiding the fragmentation

483
00:29:14.044 --> 00:29:17.984
between them, between risk assessment on one side, detection

484
00:29:18.004 --> 00:29:20.504
and risk reduction, is really something critical.

485
00:29:20.964 --> 00:29:24.924
And, a very important aspect is that we need to build that at

486
00:29:25.004 --> 00:29:28.084
a public health level, and that's really critical.

487
00:29:28.504 --> 00:29:31.744
So of course, primal prevention is public health.

488
00:29:32.084 --> 00:29:35.984
Personalized prevention will be a part of the prevention that will first

489
00:29:36.104 --> 00:29:39.564
be at a public health level. So we need to know how to

490
00:29:39.724 --> 00:29:43.664
deliver this prevention at public health level, but also will feed the

491
00:29:43.704 --> 00:29:46.614
primal prevention field of course. That's very interesting.

492
00:29:47.294 --> 00:29:51.284
So personalized prevention uses the same exposome analysis,

493
00:29:51.384 --> 00:29:54.564
the understanding of cancer biology, but we use more

494
00:29:54.624 --> 00:29:58.584
personal factors, biomarkers, intrinsic factors, to

495
00:29:58.644 --> 00:30:02.464
be able to drive the prevention for one single individual.

496
00:30:02.904 --> 00:30:06.464
So how do we build personalized cancer prevention?

497
00:30:06.884 --> 00:30:08.384
First of all, I think it's very important.

498
00:30:08.564 --> 00:30:12.494
First rule is identify citizen needs and wishes, and not

499
00:30:12.524 --> 00:30:16.504
just ours, not just, of course, the epidemiology is there, the costs are

500
00:30:16.624 --> 00:30:19.484
there, but what do the citizens want?

501
00:30:19.524 --> 00:30:23.164
And we've tried to build something that is really based also on the

502
00:30:23.224 --> 00:30:25.204
citizens' needs and wishes, the people.

503
00:30:25.734 --> 00:30:29.234
And then, of course, we need to build what we've seen today and during this

504
00:30:29.284 --> 00:30:32.884
meeting. New risk assessment means early detection

505
00:30:32.924 --> 00:30:35.924
biomarkers and tools, risk reduction strategies.

506
00:30:36.304 --> 00:30:39.244
But also beyond that, there is a lot we need

507
00:30:39.284 --> 00:30:43.054
towards implementing. So digital tools,

508
00:30:43.124 --> 00:30:46.708
artificial intelligence tools, and biomarkersValidation

509
00:30:46.788 --> 00:30:50.408
strategies at the public health levels, implementation frameworks,

510
00:30:50.548 --> 00:30:52.028
guidelines, we need guidelines,

511
00:30:53.188 --> 00:30:56.448
and developing the proper care pathways. That's a big question.

512
00:30:56.548 --> 00:30:59.028
What are the care pathways for personalized prevention?

513
00:30:59.088 --> 00:31:02.988
Who is in charge, et cetera? And at the end, support individuals

514
00:31:03.028 --> 00:31:06.208
and society towards change. That's really something.

515
00:31:06.788 --> 00:31:10.728
So what we identify is that there are some checkpoints here very early,

516
00:31:10.868 --> 00:31:14.788
and it's really important, and there's a very big French program that is

517
00:31:15.428 --> 00:31:19.308
currently being launched that is transversal not only to oncology, and

518
00:31:19.328 --> 00:31:23.248
its transversality is quite important in other fields

519
00:31:23.268 --> 00:31:27.168
but oncology, beside oncology, but also it's transversal,

520
00:31:27.508 --> 00:31:31.108
with a crosstalk between the biomarker development, even the

521
00:31:31.168 --> 00:31:33.788
basic science, and the implementation,

522
00:31:34.868 --> 00:31:36.888
the interventional research, et cetera.

523
00:31:37.278 --> 00:31:41.088
And what we identified is that the early preparation and accompanying of

524
00:31:41.148 --> 00:31:43.308
new prevention strategies is critical.

525
00:31:44.088 --> 00:31:45.928
First of all, if we want to afford for it,

526
00:31:46.888 --> 00:31:50.828
so the early health economic modeling of intervention is really critical, but

527
00:31:50.908 --> 00:31:54.648
also the acceptability, the social-psychological frameworks, the

528
00:31:54.708 --> 00:31:58.608
preparedness, et cetera, so that we don't build things that will not be

529
00:31:58.728 --> 00:32:02.708
used in the long term. And we'll see during this presentation

530
00:32:02.728 --> 00:32:06.468
that we have many such examples. So very

531
00:32:06.508 --> 00:32:08.608
rapidly, what is the state of the art currently?

532
00:32:08.648 --> 00:32:12.428
What do we have in terms of risk assessment and stratification for

533
00:32:12.468 --> 00:32:15.928
this personalized prevention? So well, breast cancer is a

534
00:32:15.948 --> 00:32:19.888
very good example. There are other ones, but I think breast cancer has been a bit

535
00:32:20.268 --> 00:32:23.808
leading the way in terms of general population.

536
00:32:24.268 --> 00:32:28.028
Risk assessment and stratification must be, of course, accurate as much as

537
00:32:28.068 --> 00:32:31.838
possible, meaningful for the people and the physicians and

538
00:32:31.908 --> 00:32:35.728
the HCPs, and actionable. And currently, we have

539
00:32:35.808 --> 00:32:39.668
a major way of identifying and stratifying breast cancer risk,

540
00:32:39.708 --> 00:32:41.748
which is based on classical scores,

541
00:32:42.948 --> 00:32:46.848
using exposures, family history, et cetera, plus timely biomarkers that

542
00:32:46.868 --> 00:32:50.628
are mostly breast density nowadays, and SNP scores,

543
00:32:50.728 --> 00:32:54.608
given the best models we have. And it took 25 years to

544
00:32:54.648 --> 00:32:58.388
come here with models that are internationally validated

545
00:32:58.428 --> 00:33:00.658
and, well, still a bit fragile, but.

546
00:33:01.288 --> 00:33:04.848
And besides that, a lot is ongoing, and developments are very

547
00:33:04.908 --> 00:33:05.388
rapidly

548
00:33:06.928 --> 00:33:10.788
arriving. And we've seen a very nice talk by Regina Barzilay two days ago

549
00:33:11.468 --> 00:33:14.988
in terms of AI, artificial intelligence assessment of

550
00:33:15.088 --> 00:33:17.188
images, and this is very true for breast.

551
00:33:17.568 --> 00:33:21.388
And apparently, what it looks like, some AI tools might be

552
00:33:21.708 --> 00:33:24.688
able to do at least as good as the classical

553
00:33:25.158 --> 00:33:28.588
predictors we have. And it's exactly the same for lung cancer.

554
00:33:28.688 --> 00:33:32.508
We classically have the PLCO model, and there are some very interesting

555
00:33:32.528 --> 00:33:34.908
image-based AI models that are arriving.

556
00:33:35.318 --> 00:33:37.738
So we might be able to better stratify and

557
00:33:38.768 --> 00:33:41.548
more easily stratify. So that was rapid.

558
00:33:41.868 --> 00:33:45.848
Now, what levels of evidence for this personalized precision prevention

559
00:33:45.948 --> 00:33:49.768
we have in clinics now? And of course, germline genetics

560
00:33:49.808 --> 00:33:52.548
have opened a path and led the way very clearly.

561
00:33:53.088 --> 00:33:57.008
So the initial precision interventions, like mentioned by the

562
00:33:57.028 --> 00:34:00.968
previous speakers, have been developed in carriers

563
00:34:01.048 --> 00:34:04.628
for BRCA, Lynch syndrome, et cetera, and especially for

564
00:34:04.748 --> 00:34:08.028
BRCA carriers that have impact on incidence and some of them the

565
00:34:08.069 --> 00:34:11.998
mortality. The level of evidence that we have are not that high because

566
00:34:12.028 --> 00:34:14.928
it never happened that a randomized control study could be

567
00:34:15.308 --> 00:34:19.028
conducted, but we have good levels, and it's really something that is implemented

568
00:34:19.089 --> 00:34:22.468
in terms of MRI, early detection for breast

569
00:34:22.548 --> 00:34:24.888
cancer, and risk reduction using

570
00:34:26.488 --> 00:34:27.748
surgery, especially.

571
00:34:29.448 --> 00:34:33.109
So well, breast cancer has been a pioneer as well in terms

572
00:34:33.328 --> 00:34:37.069
of population-based stratification, the

573
00:34:37.109 --> 00:34:39.868
tools that we have seen before in terms of risk assessment.

574
00:34:39.917 --> 00:34:43.468
So where are we in terms of risk-based breast cancer screening?

575
00:34:43.548 --> 00:34:47.368
Because this is the first place this stratification has been to, and

576
00:34:47.448 --> 00:34:51.348
I've worked a lot on that. So it's already in place for

577
00:34:51.488 --> 00:34:54.788
specific populations, as we mentioned, carriers, et cetera.

578
00:34:54.948 --> 00:34:58.908
MRI for dense breast, two positive randomized trials, but unfortunately,

579
00:34:59.908 --> 00:35:03.848
the feasibility is very poor, and that's a big problem.

580
00:35:04.028 --> 00:35:07.508
They're, again, developing something that at the end is not affordable, not

581
00:35:07.548 --> 00:35:11.488
feasible because it's too expensive, and the access is difficult for MRI.

582
00:35:12.508 --> 00:35:16.288
That's a bit critical. So the risk identification, there we

583
00:35:16.408 --> 00:35:19.888
are, and the general population level risk-based screening strategies

584
00:35:20.088 --> 00:35:21.448
almost there at a level

585
00:35:22.408 --> 00:35:26.128
1A evidence, not yet there. And we had the

586
00:35:26.688 --> 00:35:29.928
results of the first randomized trial, the US trial wisdom,

587
00:35:30.788 --> 00:35:34.728
a few months ago. It was a non-inferiority trial that compared a

588
00:35:34.888 --> 00:35:37.448
stratified strategy versus standard screening.

589
00:35:38.088 --> 00:35:41.928
The primary endpoint was incidence of Stage 2B breast cancer, but

590
00:35:42.028 --> 00:35:42.448
also

591
00:35:43.528 --> 00:35:47.488
the advent of false positives. It was positive only

592
00:35:47.548 --> 00:35:51.208
on this primary endpoint, Stage

593
00:35:51.388 --> 00:35:55.028
2B, and it's a non-inferiority trial, so as you see here.

594
00:35:55.978 --> 00:35:59.768
So it's a first step. It was a bit underpowered, but a very

595
00:35:59.928 --> 00:36:03.788
important first step. So in Europe, we have launched this trial

596
00:36:04.348 --> 00:36:08.108
many years ago. It's the MIPEPS trials that compares in women 40 to

597
00:36:08.828 --> 00:36:12.508
70 a randomized comparison

598
00:36:12.548 --> 00:36:16.508
between standard screening during four years versus risk-based

599
00:36:16.568 --> 00:36:20.428
screening. If your risk is assessed to be low, you get your next mammogram

600
00:36:20.488 --> 00:36:24.428
in four years. If the risk is higher than average, you get a yearly mammogram or

601
00:36:24.488 --> 00:36:27.808
even an MRI, but not all the population will get MRI, of course.

602
00:36:28.228 --> 00:36:31.708
The primary endpoint is the incidence of Stage 2 and higher breast cancer.

603
00:36:32.108 --> 00:36:35.928
And it's very interesting that we built that at the population level, and we

604
00:36:35.988 --> 00:36:37.188
inserted this in

605
00:36:38.048 --> 00:36:41.848
existing programs of organized screening in each country, six

606
00:36:41.888 --> 00:36:45.368
countries, four years of inclusion, and the primary endpoint will be

607
00:36:45.428 --> 00:36:49.308
available in 2027. So it's really been, hopefully, a big step

608
00:36:49.368 --> 00:36:51.337
towards this risk stratification.

609
00:36:51.968 --> 00:36:53.008
So what did we learn

610
00:36:53.968 --> 00:36:57.864
about MIPEPS?So far. So first of all, it's interesting to see that

611
00:36:57.904 --> 00:37:01.604
the short-term delivery of a PEARS score was very feasible.

612
00:37:02.144 --> 00:37:04.564
Median turnaround time was seven weeks.

613
00:37:04.624 --> 00:37:05.944
It was all academic

614
00:37:07.004 --> 00:37:10.404
for 28,000 samples, so that's very feasible.

615
00:37:11.304 --> 00:37:14.844
Probably less feasible than having an AI reading the

616
00:37:14.884 --> 00:37:16.664
mammogram, of course, but it's not bad.

617
00:37:17.484 --> 00:37:19.644
In terms of risk categories, quite meaningful.

618
00:37:19.724 --> 00:37:20.084
We had

619
00:37:21.304 --> 00:37:24.064
low-risk category, 36% of the population.

620
00:37:24.644 --> 00:37:27.584
The mean age was 54 to 55,

621
00:37:28.444 --> 00:37:32.364
and we have 33% of the population that is identified at high risk.

622
00:37:32.464 --> 00:37:34.344
The high risk is quite conservative, it's

623
00:37:34.604 --> 00:37:38.493
1.67% invasive breast cancer risk at five

624
00:37:38.544 --> 00:37:42.114
years. And it's a very low amount that is at very high risk,

625
00:37:42.384 --> 00:37:46.264
1.37. By age group, it's very different, so

626
00:37:46.304 --> 00:37:49.884
it allows to stratify, of course, differently according to age.

627
00:37:51.004 --> 00:37:52.144
We recently compared

628
00:37:52.964 --> 00:37:56.804
the MIPEPS stratification versus the same stratification

629
00:37:56.844 --> 00:37:59.504
UK Biobank, and indeed it looks the same.

630
00:37:59.564 --> 00:38:03.264
So it's something at the population level that is reproducible.

631
00:38:03.764 --> 00:38:07.344
We know that it's not exactly the same at the individual level, of course.

632
00:38:08.904 --> 00:38:12.284
Well, we looked at how women were interested,

633
00:38:12.844 --> 00:38:16.684
not really in risk-based screening, but in entering the trial.

634
00:38:16.764 --> 00:38:19.024
So it's not exactly the same. It's a mix of both.

635
00:38:20.024 --> 00:38:23.724
In MIPEPS, we have an over-representation of educated women, and

636
00:38:24.104 --> 00:38:27.084
you know that it's true for any clinical trial.

637
00:38:27.634 --> 00:38:29.924
So we have a 50% of the population

638
00:38:30.884 --> 00:38:34.324
with a high educational level, and it's only 13%

639
00:38:34.984 --> 00:38:38.684
with very low education level, and 2.4% materially

640
00:38:38.724 --> 00:38:41.804
deprived, which is quite standard in Europe.

641
00:38:42.144 --> 00:38:46.044
So that's always an issue. It's an issue with the trial, but we need to

642
00:38:46.104 --> 00:38:49.684
make sure that it will not be an issue with the risk-based screening in the

643
00:38:49.724 --> 00:38:52.624
future. Comprehension was very good.

644
00:38:52.964 --> 00:38:56.884
The women at baseline really comprehended very well what it was about,

645
00:38:56.944 --> 00:39:00.364
so that was very reassuring. And sorry for the typo.

646
00:39:00.424 --> 00:39:04.263
We looked at the sociodemographic characteristic that impacted the

647
00:39:04.344 --> 00:39:07.424
acceptance to participate in a trial that was in Spain.

648
00:39:07.904 --> 00:39:11.564
And indeed, higher education level and higher

649
00:39:11.664 --> 00:39:15.484
income is really linked to participation in the trial.

650
00:39:15.984 --> 00:39:19.944
It is unclear whether it's just a trial or it's risk-based screening

651
00:39:19.984 --> 00:39:21.034
itself. But

652
00:39:22.004 --> 00:39:24.934
that's very important to know for the future implementation.

653
00:39:25.464 --> 00:39:28.824
Very important as well, healthcare professionals' acceptability,

654
00:39:29.304 --> 00:39:33.004
and especially in terms of risk communication.

655
00:39:33.064 --> 00:39:37.044
So we had almost 800 healthcare professional involved in the

656
00:39:37.124 --> 00:39:38.644
trial in the different countries.

657
00:39:39.064 --> 00:39:42.824
Some of them very trained, some of them we trained with the trial, but not so much

658
00:39:42.984 --> 00:39:46.724
trained. The majority was rather comfortable with risk

659
00:39:46.804 --> 00:39:50.784
announcement, but a minority is very comfortable, especially

660
00:39:50.824 --> 00:39:54.724
for low risk categories. Some of them did not like it, especially

661
00:39:54.824 --> 00:39:58.194
radiologists for some reason. So what is clear is that

662
00:39:58.244 --> 00:40:00.264
education and training is needed.

663
00:40:00.664 --> 00:40:04.604
But the big question is: Who are the right HCPs to deliver that

664
00:40:04.644 --> 00:40:08.364
kind of personalized prevention, or person prevention?

665
00:40:08.424 --> 00:40:11.084
It's really unclear to us. So we had this

666
00:40:12.384 --> 00:40:15.484
mixed method study in France recently, because in France, the

667
00:40:15.564 --> 00:40:19.404
official physicians or healthcare professionals in charge of

668
00:40:19.504 --> 00:40:23.384
prevention are GPs. So we did a mixed method study among

669
00:40:23.464 --> 00:40:27.124
GPs. And while GPs really thought that it was their

670
00:40:27.204 --> 00:40:31.144
duty to do cancer prevention, there were very few levels that we could

671
00:40:31.284 --> 00:40:34.744
identify, mostly cognitive, not really emotional, and many

672
00:40:34.824 --> 00:40:38.704
barriers. You know about that. Limited engagement, lack of time,

673
00:40:38.824 --> 00:40:42.184
absence of reward, competitive activities, et cetera.

674
00:40:42.284 --> 00:40:45.984
And they really knew little about personalized prevention approaches.

675
00:40:46.624 --> 00:40:50.364
So there again, we need really training or identifying the right people to

676
00:40:50.404 --> 00:40:54.264
deliver this care. So what are the current strategies and tools for

677
00:40:54.304 --> 00:40:56.304
personalized prevention of cancer,

678
00:40:57.204 --> 00:41:00.824
and risk reduction especially? What tools do we have at our disposal?

679
00:41:02.324 --> 00:41:06.304
We have lifetime modifications that potentially could be very powerful, but

680
00:41:06.364 --> 00:41:09.664
they require major political efforts and dedicated healthcare

681
00:41:09.704 --> 00:41:13.674
organizations. Local treatments, that's for carriers,

682
00:41:13.764 --> 00:41:17.024
very high risk. And drugs, vaccine, we've seen that this is

683
00:41:17.243 --> 00:41:21.144
really a very interesting field. So if we look at the uptake

684
00:41:21.244 --> 00:41:22.264
rate so far,

685
00:41:24.384 --> 00:41:28.104
as a function of the magnitude of the expected risk benefit, it's

686
00:41:28.124 --> 00:41:31.824
very variable. So the best uptake is for HPV

687
00:41:31.864 --> 00:41:34.704
vaccine and salpingo-oophorectomy for carriers.

688
00:41:34.744 --> 00:41:38.364
For mastectomy, it's a lot less. Unfortunately, tobacco

689
00:41:38.444 --> 00:41:42.144
cessation, alcohol cessation, which have a very good

690
00:41:42.224 --> 00:41:45.284
impact on risk reduction, have not a very good uptake.

691
00:41:45.824 --> 00:41:49.504
And some others that represent a lot of people in the population

692
00:41:49.844 --> 00:41:53.784
have both not a huge magnitude of expected benefit,

693
00:41:53.864 --> 00:41:57.504
but it's still there, and an uptake rate that is not really good.

694
00:41:57.564 --> 00:42:00.284
So we need to work on interventions that would have

695
00:42:01.144 --> 00:42:01.644
a very

696
00:42:03.064 --> 00:42:05.984
important expected benefit, but also very good

697
00:42:06.904 --> 00:42:07.344
uptake.

698
00:42:08.224 --> 00:42:11.324
With the ESMO prevention committee, we looked at

699
00:42:11.364 --> 00:42:15.304
in 92 randomized trials that have tested drug-based cancer

700
00:42:15.364 --> 00:42:18.944
prevention so far. It's only 92 in whole cancer

701
00:42:18.984 --> 00:42:22.684
history. 50 of them were positive, but you know that the

702
00:42:22.704 --> 00:42:25.984
implementation was very rare at the end.

703
00:42:26.024 --> 00:42:28.504
It's only HPV vaccines and some endocrine

704
00:42:30.384 --> 00:42:31.964
drugs that have been implemented.

705
00:42:32.404 --> 00:42:36.024
And we looked at the predictors of success or failures of these

706
00:42:36.164 --> 00:42:38.104
trials. And it is very interesting to see that

707
00:42:38.944 --> 00:42:42.524
the trials that were sponsored for pharma companies had five

708
00:42:42.604 --> 00:42:45.164
times more odds to success.

709
00:42:46.324 --> 00:42:50.064
And it was very reduced for non-specific drugs, and

710
00:42:52.284 --> 00:42:55.904
with a lower pre-trial evidence, you had one third of the odds

711
00:42:55.984 --> 00:42:58.524
to have success. So pre-trial evidence is very

712
00:42:58.544 --> 00:43:01.780
important.Another aspect of prevention is the

713
00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:05.460
acceptability, the desirability of the drug prevention.

714
00:43:05.980 --> 00:43:09.200
And we have recently published this French trial, LIBER,

715
00:43:09.870 --> 00:43:11.880
that proposed a randomized study.

716
00:43:11.920 --> 00:43:14.480
It was letrozole versus placebo for carriers.

717
00:43:14.930 --> 00:43:18.320
And unfortunately, we had only an 18% trial

718
00:43:18.380 --> 00:43:22.100
acceptance among carriers, and the five-year adherence was quite

719
00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:25.880
low, 75%. And it ended up in an underpowered

720
00:43:25.980 --> 00:43:27.360
study with no

721
00:43:28.460 --> 00:43:31.320
observed effect on risk reduction.

722
00:43:32.580 --> 00:43:35.280
So how can we overcome implementation barriers?

723
00:43:35.920 --> 00:43:38.200
What are the challenges? Many challenges.

724
00:43:38.240 --> 00:43:42.040
Delivering risk assessment at public health level, justice, equity,

725
00:43:42.300 --> 00:43:46.200
affordability, a desired intervention, unification

726
00:43:46.280 --> 00:43:49.260
between risk assessment, detection, and prevention, as I said.

727
00:43:49.680 --> 00:43:53.360
With HCPs, guidelines, training, education,

728
00:43:53.480 --> 00:43:56.620
convincing the patients and the society, and

729
00:43:56.720 --> 00:44:00.070
organizing the anticipation and the

730
00:44:00.080 --> 00:44:03.930
agility that is needed to implement the new drugs,

731
00:44:04.020 --> 00:44:07.480
the new tools that are arriving. In France, we have launched this

732
00:44:07.500 --> 00:44:09.180
program five years ago.

733
00:44:10.720 --> 00:44:14.500
It's a pilot program. We call it interception program.

734
00:44:14.540 --> 00:44:18.480
It's a mixed community hospital, digital program that leads

735
00:44:18.560 --> 00:44:21.280
to the identification of high-risk individuals in the

736
00:44:22.080 --> 00:44:25.920
community by HCPs, one-stop shops of

737
00:44:25.960 --> 00:44:28.600
